Ùª­jAttributesÙ¯‚€öpExtended SummaryÙ¯‚Ù¹‚Ù§yThis function uses the Difference of Gaussians method for applying band-pass filters to multi-dimensional arrays. The input array is blurred with two Gaussian kernels of differing sigmas to produce two intermediate, filtered images. The more-blurred image is then subtracted from the less-blurred image. The final output image will therefore have had high-frequency components attenuated by the smaller-sigma Gaussian, and low frequency components will have been removed due to their presence in the more-blurred intermediate.€ögMethodsÙ¯‚€öeNotesÙ¯‚„Ù¹‚‹Ù§xZThis function will subtract an array filtered with a Gaussian kernel with sigmas given by Ù¡jhigh_sigmaÙ§xG from an array filtered with a Gaussian kernel with sigmas provided by Ù¡ilow_sigmaÙ§q. The values for Ù¡jhigh_sigmaÙ§xE must always be greater than or equal to the corresponding values in Ù¡ilow_sigmaÙ§g, or a Ù¡jValueErrorÙ§p will be raised.€Ù¹‚‡Ù§eWhen Ù¡jhigh_sigmaÙ§x is none, the values for Ù¡jhigh_sigmaÙ§x8 will be calculated as 1.6x the corresponding values in Ù¡ilow_sigmaÙ§x·. This ratio was originally proposed by Marr and Hildreth (1980)  and is commonly used when approximating the inverted Laplacian of Gaussian, which is used in edge and blob detection.€Ù¹‚ƒÙ§x9Input image is converted according to the conventions of Ù¡limg_as_floatÙ§a.€Ù¹‚Ù§xBExcept for sigma values, all parameters are used for both filters.€öpOther ParametersÙ¯‚€öjParametersÙ¯‚‡Ù°ƒeimagegndarrayÙ¹‚Ù§vInput array to filter.€Ù°ƒilow_sigmaxscalar or sequence of scalarsÙ¹‚Ù§yStandard deviation(s) for the Gaussian kernel with the smaller sigmas across all axes. The standard deviations are given for each axis as a sequence, or as a single number, in which case the single number is used as the standard deviation value for all axes.€Ù°ƒjhigh_sigmax9scalar or sequence of scalars, optional (default is None)Ù¹‚Ù§yTStandard deviation(s) for the Gaussia